TY  - JOUR
AU  - Hecht, Peter
AU  - Vuolteenaho, Tuomo
T1  - Explaining Returns with Cash-Flow Proxies
PY  - 2006
Y1  - 2006/03/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhj001
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 19
IS  - 1
SP  - 159
EP  - 194
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Stock returns are correlated with contemporaneous earnings growth, dividend growth, future real activity, and other cash-flow proxies. The correlation between cash-flow proxies and stock returns may arise from association of cash-flow proxies with one-period expected returns, cash-flow news, and/or expected-return news. We use Campbell’s (1991) return decomposition to measure the relative importance of these three effects in regressions of returns on cash-flow proxies. In some of the popular specifications, variables that are motivated as proxies for cash-flow news also track a nontrivial proportion of one-period expected returns and expected-return news. As a result, the R2 from a regression of returns on cash-flow proxies may overstate or understate the importance of cash-flow news as a source of return variance.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhj001
ER  - 



